The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, there is something missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Perhaps this one will not be kept waiting for long.
That the Czech mobile service providers work at the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
This also confirmed the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price for a text message here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps of the European Commission in the regulation of roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile service providers SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really makes a fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of well over 100%.
However, mobile telephone providers are happy to complain that there is an extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
This is often also the responsibility of the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who had often stated in the past that there was no place for another supplier in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network will no longer have a lot of opportunities (by the way, he would probably not find any frequencies).
But there is one other option - a virtual provider.
The entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought with it a significant price reduction, which the classic mobile service providers had to react to.
There were similar votes to those in the Czech Republic before such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't need to look for examples for a long time.
In February of this we reported on the start of the virtual provider mobilizing in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the fifth largest provider in the country.
The financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind mobilisation.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, the virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilization in Poland shows, it can also be a good move to focus on a non-clarifying target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Echte Kerle wählen Mobilking - the provider they like and trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept could be adopted in the Czech Republic as in Poland.
The press spokesperson of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In the Czech Republic, the mobile service providers mean without a chance
However, it is almost certain that when a virtual mobile service provider conquers Czech Republic, this will not be mobilisation.
"We speak of an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look particularly hopeful.
Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesperson of the financial group Penta, says in a telephone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková in other countries of our region.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to do so.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything in their power to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
For a long time, your interest in launching a virtual mobile service provider has been showing the GTS Novera group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the earlier, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile service providers.
With some of them we have already been able to reach negotiations," said the press spokesperson of Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe now's a better time.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specificities in relation to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the Press Department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
The press spokesperson at T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds, in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "Up to now, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build further."
And she adds: "The network of T-Mobile will hardly show up a virtual provider until the end of the year.
At that moment we should already have a concrete offer to be able to think so in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický comments: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is exactly what we consider to be the best from the point of view of customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area lies in the search for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
It is easy to understand the behaviour of mobile operators, another provider was called more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
Why, then, should such a competitor be facilitated to enter the market?
The fact that providers can draw on a string when it comes to something also proves the long way to and fro about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ was out of the company T-Mobile at the time when U:fon came to market.
This is also evidenced by the information available to the public from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is right to argue why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently also been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile service provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new player in the market itself and in particular its services would impose high requirements."
However, in view of this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is astounded.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately, unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It has exclusively the office to protect economic competition (ÚOHS).
But this refers to the whole problem of his very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile service provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile service provider and a virtual provider through the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such agreement has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," said Kristianan Chalupa in his reply to our request from the ÚOHS External Relations Department.
Representatives of the providers would not be surprised at such a wording.
This is more than a concern of a public authority representing consumer interests and, among other things, of ensuring that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, if Kristianán Chalupa adds: "In other countries, where virtual providers work normally, it can be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
But probably the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are not part of the interests of ÚOHS.
Really shocking in this case is the almost touching consistency of the three mobile service providers resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is on hand.
Just as the very same price of petrol at the gas stations is certainly only coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"In this case, the Authority has not identified any signs of anti-competitive action and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so it does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for its market operations.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are probably also missing from the telecommunications regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by the ČTÚ, after which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, none of the Czech mobile service providers have a dominant position in such a market.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile service provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that he necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile service providers behave in strikingly similar ways.
Complaints by a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) demonstrate that they face very similar obstacles during negotiations with all suppliers.
The shifting of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment of the Telecommunications Act did not implement the extension of the ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this all too well, but probably they have other interests.
It's okay when no one's looking.
Without notice, the operation of any pseudo-virtual provider, of whom there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
They are usually companies operating in the multi-level marketing sector.
Personal mobile phone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke is that the company acts as a classic business customer to the operator, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile telecommunications providers prohibit similar types of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it can be a violation of the contractual terms with which we will then deal, which may lead to the termination of cooperation with the corresponding society," Martina Kemrová answered our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not apply to the operators responsible for mobile communications.
In particular, in the case of the three mentioned companies, it may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such action.
In fact, the activities of these companies do not lead to negligible profits, while, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such kinds of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have full control over it as the normal customers of the mobile service providers."
However, the ČTÚ would have to be at least strange.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
Before such a procedure, mobile operators close their eyes, why lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It is to be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to discover such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to satisfy itself with the declaration of the providers, they knew nothing about it and their terms and conditions would forbid it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As the text has been pointed out several times, the market entry of virtual providers led to a significant price decline in the various services.
In practice, in all countries where virtual providers have emerged, classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence virtually more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies, which did not attempt to protect the interests of mobile communications providers, but which were trying to protect their customers, intervened in precisely these moments.
If it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator arose, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies reject themselves as a hot potato all the time.
Based on our experience, we cannot dismiss the impression that in these cases ignorance in competences is more than favorable.
But let's not throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider is soon emerging, the Czech mobile market may soon be moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the ÚOHS will not remain ineffective when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other stakeholders.
And the Czechs will not finally call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
