For years a mysterious phenomenon has caused confusion among scientists - the Swing-by-Anomaly.
The Swing-by is a flight manoeuvre of space probes in which they receive additional momentum in the gravitational field of a heavenly body, such as the Earth.
This allows the probes to save a lot of fuel.
The Cassini-Huygen European-American research probe used this physical trick as well as the Ulysses solar probe.
But what the researchers have been amazed at for years: the missiles do not behave 100 percent as expected by the old-fashioned gravitational law.
Rather, there are irregularities at the speed.
The probes are unexpectedly getting faster or slower.
So far, physicists have not been able to explain this effect.
They named him Swing-by-Anomaly.
Some experts fear that perhaps even the general theory of relativity of Albert Einstein, which describes the attraction of matter through a crumbling of space, could not be quite right.
American physicist Stephen Adler of the Institute for Advanced Study from Princeton still firmly believes that Einstein was not mistaken, and tries to explain the Swing-by-Anomaly with the help of so-called dark matter that astronomers have formed in the universe.
"Less for the anomaly could be dark matter, which could also be very close to the earth," he writes.
The space researchers have only known about the existence of dark matter for around ten years.
It obviously assumes an attraction whose effect on other heavenly bodies can be observed.
On the other hand, it itself is completely invisible, that is, it sends and does not reflect any electromagnetic radiation, especially no visible light.
After all, the dark matter, according to the calculations of the scientists, accounts for a fifth of the total mass of the universe.
