Debate on bilingual education: Education in English-speaking environments
In this edition of the "Education Watch", Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, head of science in California studies and director of the Department of Education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as good as you think: why the middle class needs a selection".
Addressing the Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama's proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama's election campaign mentions that "the probability of successful school completion in African-American and Hispanic students is lower than in white students" - what is true.
In order to close this gap, Obama's education plan recommends, among other things, a bilingual transition phase in training for those who learn English first.
The question to Obama, however, is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the distance in education.
Consider Sixth Street Prep, a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from families with low incomes.
More than one third of students, many of whom have only recently been in the country, learn English.
Nevertheless, in 2008 an amazing 100 percent of fourth-class students passed the state exam in Mathe at a good level.
Also surprising were 93 percent of children from the fourth year of school assessed well in English exams.
This amazing success has been achieved with methods other than those preferred by Obama.
The Sixth Street School focuses on checking and exercising, on continuous control of knowledge and a position that does not tolerate exceptions.
