A flamenco dancer from Seville honors a dancer who is also from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Katalane (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and the mother Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the Triana district and when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and expert for oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first fighters to emancipate the woman, such as Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, a vegetarian, and opposed the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
The life of this woman, who left her traces of the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe in the time between the wars, fascinated Isabel Bayón.
`I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this role to me, which seemed impossible to me.'
'We're not trying to tell about her life without keeping her Esprit,' said the flamenco dancer.
Your dance bases helped me in Flamenco a lot.
`The dance of the butterfly' appeared to me, for example, like Guajira, or 'the dance of the snake' like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I've been told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area', she claims.
The staging is based on two extraordinary collaborations: with Miguel Poveda, who will sing for Isabel at one of their performances, as he did in `La puerta aberera'; and with flamenco master Matilde Coral, who wanted to work with one of her ex-students.
`Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I feel very honoured.'
The staging also counts with musical composition and guitarists Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the singing of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Juarez, he assumes the role of the companion of the artists who were Divas, in whom he repeatedly falls in love.'
This work also tells in a certain way of the life of this woman, who has been known in such far-reaching places as India, the United States or Russia, and also throughout Europe, although she has normally lived in London.
'I wanted to call her back in memory, because I think she is one of the women who have a huge influence on a particular era and whose works are no longer of value today, and therefore they know even less', says Bayón.
