The car drivers, who can fall back because of the alcohol level, will have to install the `Alcolock'.
The authority orders that the driver, who had three official penalties for alcohol levels, install in his car this system, which forbids him to start the car in a drunken state. If he is alcoholized, then the car does not jump.
The initiative has already been announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the Public Prosecutor General's Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last for a year.
The purpose is to re-socialise the driver, which is why he is given a price for re-education of the traffic.
In addition to the Public Prosecutor-General's Office, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for the Safety of Automobiles will be involved in this.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of drivers, who were shown more than once as a result of driving under alcohol, went back to work.
The `alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the breathed air and prevents the start of the car when the driver has performed the alcohol test; or if an alcohol concentration is found which is higher than permitted.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, the costs are borne by the person who imposes the penalty.
In this context, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that already in the first year after its introduction, equipped cars prevent up to 65% of the regulatory breaches.
In Spain, 115 lives could be saved annually.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to attack this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate its implementation, a legal reform can be implemented in the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the basic law is required which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The device is still available on the Spanish markets, in no business, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and vehicles of public transport.
Tomorrow, the House of Representatives will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, which has already been done in France.
