Discussion - From blood that has been safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of her founding, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence, which was shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves administered by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994 the Government of Canada launched a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and working out guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to report, several provinces then set up a committee to develop a new system for the administration of blood preserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, who is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started working, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood-staining system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and through the work in this area over the following years, we have regained public confidence', she says, before she proudly emphasises that by the beginning of 2008 almost 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps aware that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At this time, we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
`And we didn't have the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we called for one of the main guidelines of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, which says that exclusion is applied if you do not know this and if a disease progresss only slowly, as it is apparently the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999 no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, it was proved that this disease was transmitted over the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution we were applying is quite meaningful.
In 1999 a much more precise technique for detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which enable the virus to be detected directly in the donor’s blood, and not the antibody against the virus, as was the case with the tests previously used.
The NST allowed to shorten the incubation time between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it and one could not recognize it was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to reduce significantly the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV - infected blood.
`In other words, you would have to distribute 12 million blood preserves before someone would be infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood canisters each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs in which HIV was transmitted via a blood canister.
I think you can feel comfortable today when you get or write a blood transfusion to restore your health', says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to get the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year has the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Western Nile virus, is transmitted by insects over the blood.
We have to keep monitoring', Dr. Décary continues before stressing that Hema-Quebec must also provide a sufficient supply in addition to a secure supply.
`The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood-supplier network, which averages only 3% of Quebec's blood-supplier population.
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and who meets the fitness criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who supply their blood are not expected to be ill with AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from the donation for one year.
`With this 3%, we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Missing supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It is hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep it and to make them regular donors.
Life is so hectic nowadays that you rarely find the time to spend an hour in blood donation', Francine Décary regrets.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood preserves but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which are used almost exclusively in severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public cord bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, considered earlier to be biomedical waste, there is rich blood on stem cells that can help treat severe diseases, such as leukaemia.
A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousands of cord blood samples, and we are planning to drop more than a thousand annually.
`We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year', Dr. Décary further explains, which describes this program as very popular for the removal of navel cord blood.
'Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
