The psychology of oversupply - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and therefore overvalue the fault bid.
Neurologists and business researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behaviour.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to give themselves in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play Lotto, while the others participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were investigated by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
The participants were able to win money at both games, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain cortex, was measured in the event of the auction’s failure, in which the opponent’s excess played an important role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore said that the price increase was explained by avoiding overreaction to the striatum.
In order to substantiate their thesis, economists in the research group have also carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their contributions.
Another group was also promised 15 dollars of reward, in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was simply that the emphasis on the one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "counter the losing" group were prepared for higher stakes than those of the control or "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
In fact, these have so far been the reasons for the behaviour observed at auctions only with the joy of winning, or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological methods, so that we now have a third explanation prepared" - said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Faculty of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor visit?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected is estimated at a hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for various virus-induced infectious liver disease.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogens, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, cleavage or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to immunise the viruses A and B at least, there is no vaccine against the virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur approximately two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
Then yellow fever appears on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine darkens, and the recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die every year from diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every 10 people infected are treated with medication.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: it can lead to untreated liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen destroys the liver cells in a debilitating manner - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who have undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
At present, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the hospital doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
In a timely manner, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thus banaging the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is the World's Day of Hepatitis, first organized in 2004 by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, their development and the importance of early detection.
