Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: It has been investigated to what extent belief in God affects human pain, reported the British newspaper "Telegraph".
During the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists received electric shocks each while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the believers were able to eliminate much of the pain.
Even brain scan technology has shown that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain control.
The study was the first in a research project in which scientists, in addition to philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university, participate.
During the test, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand, which the electric shocks gave off.
The participants were asked to focus strongly on two paintings: on the one hand, a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other, Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the vision of the Virgin Mary would produce a kind of religious trance among the faithful, while they chose da Vinci's image, because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt calming.
The test subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages during that time, while they should either view the religious, or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt "in security" at the sight of the Mother of God as if they were "careful" and felt "peace and peace".
While viewing the religious painting, they reported more than 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be produced among the atheists with other highly active images, but only the corresponding photo would have to be found.
