Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method for developing new technologies to avoid accidents if they did not imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, those of bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented which inspired the Nissan engineers of Hummeln in creating new systems of accident prevention.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system controlled by Autobots, a mini-car, equipped with the properties of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private" area, which is very similar to our own "protective shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
To imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers picked up the idea of the laser-controlled distanceometer.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a 180 degree field of vision within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of seconds, and the Autobot immediately changes the price, similar to the movement of bees, by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If not, the author could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, Head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Autobot Project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer in which accidents are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of bees when they avoid other bees.
And that has to be done in the fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, the deviation cannot be made down, or even diagonally - it can only be two dimensional, i.e. only in the direction of the rotation of the tires.
While the bees are endlessly open here to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use the Autobot only the rotational movement, or acceleration and braking.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life span than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it comes to the instinctive, intelligent response, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical response using previous maneuvers, so that it is currently only a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabytes and megabytes of heavy memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision avoidance technology, which according to Nissan's assessment will be in production as a whole within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately steering the car driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
