Napolitano: "Preventing accidents at work is crucial"
Every day in Italy 2500 accidents at work, three people die and 27 remain disabled for life.
For 2007, the data from Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were approximately 1200.
These figures prove the seriousness of a phenomenon which causes almost twice as many deaths as murder.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalididi del Lavoro) in all the provinces of Italy will commit the 58th National Day for the Victims of Accidents to draw the attention of the social institutions and the media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention at work is," affirms the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The Head of State expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to the prevention of jobs, the protection of injured workers, the support of the families of the victims and the awareness of the public opinion".
"An insolent "basta" has stood up to this; understandablely, in the case of tragedies, which, measured by their scale, trigger some whirlwinds in the media and public intervention. However, everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events that can even be repeated in their own dynamics".
Napolitano does not hide that "there is in any case a resource problem: there must be a decisive investment in education and information."
A special importance is attached to the numerous initiatives to become more directly aware of the school frameworks of young people who feed on the labour market.
It is our duty to focus attention on this phenomenon and not to divert it from its social seriousness. A legislative standard must be put into force and improved.
On the other hand, the President of the Chamber of Gianfranco Fini stressed "like the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency, which offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards decisive rules that aim to put an end to the problem".
"The data of the accidents at work seem to signal a slight improvement, but this does not rule out that the number of accidents at work is much too high," stresses President of Anmil, Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this "positive tendency" to mean less attention. That's exactly what causes tragedy at the end."
"How do you think that you are essentially doing too little to counter the phenomenon of accidents? You can fight against it through various actions.
We believe that stronger controls and inspections are necessary – according to Mercandelli, but also stronger measures to inform workers who are already starting school".
"An additional effort is needed - so he adds - in terms of communication and awareness-raising of the public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers is called for in relation to a phenomenon that is a social emergency".
Mercandelli also pointed out "the progressive deterioration of protection for the victims of accidents at work" and addressed the "disposal of the social system against which we have been fighting in recent years".
"The aim, therefore, is to return a guarantee to the worker on insurance so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not depend on voluntary or accidental donations, which are decided by a legislator at the moment".
Mp3 Player Under Charge: Danger of Hearing Damage
Sound music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as Mp3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission reports, which cites the opinion of the Csrseri (Scientific Committee on Current and Recently Identified Health Risks) of the EU in a report published today in Brussels.
"From the report – as stated in a note – it becomes clear that 5-10% of those who hear loud music with portable music for at least five years per week, with a permanent loss of their hearing, are at risk of hearing for at least one hour a day".
"I'm worried that such a large number of young people, who usually use portable music devices and cell phones, put on a high volume to damage their hearing without knowing it irrevocably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings – that is, from the European Union – there is a clear risk that is pressing for rapid action.
What really counts is to raise awareness of consumers and turn this information into a common resource.
In the light of these scientific findings, we need to re-examine the existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology".
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable musical instruments among young people.
"The scientists - thus concluding the EU communication - confirm that we are quite concerned and that the European Commission, together with the other members of the European Union and those concerned, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music devices and similar devices."
There is already a European standard, which limits the level of noise from portable music devices to 100 dB, and concerns about the damage that could result from excessive noise pollution.
It is possible to limit these damage to solutions such as the reduction of volume and the length of noise exposure.
In her report, the Scientific Committee of the European Union points out that if users of portable music devices are only five hours a week (more than 89 decibels) music, so that the legal limits are already exceeded, the maximum noise level at the workplace applies.
Those who cross this border risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This represents 5-10% of users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
