The superglue that goes up on walls
To defeat the forces of gravity thanks to a adhesive and to be able to climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which seems to have reached almost the target.
With a glue applied on an area of only 2.5 sqcm, the researchers succeeded in fixing a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
STUDIO – an American magazine, has published the results of the researchers at the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team of researchers is a further development of the adhesives already used, which use a special carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of a stack of spaghetti arranged pipes," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists have been inspired by the feet of Geckos, which are covered by microscopic herds that give the animal a perfect hold.
The tests carried out with various materials such as glass Teflon and sand paper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the durability of the feet of the reptiles and at the same time "makes it easy to remove from the wall," said Liming Dai, researcher of the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
"This material could be used as a perishable adhesive," Liming Dai adds.
Like Spiderman, to get up on walls? Perhaps already, but the researchers think of less fascinating benefits, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other areas of application may fall within the space sector.
So for the moment, the superheroes still have to wait.
The other kind of research – also the University of Berkeley, California, is dedicated to a new type of adhesive.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the California scientists present a adhesive made of microfibres that, like hair, cleanses itself from dust by moving on a surface and thus always retains perfect liability.
Medicines: never take fruit juice
Be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed in summer due to their refreshing quality and richness of vitamins, can cause serious health damage when taken at the same time as certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these drinks by the body.
David Bailey, professor of the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points to the risk of packaged fruit juices as well as fresh fruit juices in connection with drug consumption. At the 236th American Chemical Society Meeting in Philadelphia, he again called for an alarm: a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice suffices to reduce the absorption of certain essential medicines to the point of practically eliminating them and thus endangering the health of the patients.
Grapefruit juice was already under suspicion of being responsible for increasing the effects of some medicines such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytics and neurologicals, up to toxic levels.
MEDICAN MEASUREMENT – The same Agency of the drug had warned doctors and patients in a report two years ago about the risks of this mixture, and stressed that what is being drunk in conjunction with drugs such as diazepan or methadone.
ES IS NOT GREEP FRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances that are inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Therefore, the appeal of Michele Carruba, Director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually forwarded immediately to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change consumer information.
Therefore, it is recommended that you always read the package leaflet and, if there is any doubt as to whether you should ask for a pharmacist or a doctor", the expert of the Ansa Agency emphasises.
