Open Office, it appears the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package
The date of publication of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has arrived; the Open Source software wins an ever greater number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in the public administration as free replacement for Microsoft's Office.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now presenting itself with some new features to the audience: besides a revised and now Spartan-designed start menu, one of the reasons for ensuring compatibility with Apple's Mac OS x operating system is finally reached, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest standard ISO version.
In addition, the compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007 was countered, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as those that allow you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes sending via email easier. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphic editing modules while keeping the original appearance of the page.
Thus, "hybrid" PDF files can now be generated, which expands the typical graphics of Adobe format around the elements of a table and a text processing system.
The cooperation is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be processed by several users, avoiding conflicts with changes; in the case of the text processing system, each processor is assigned a basket to ensure a better correction process.
Some companies are just about to publish various functions of OpenOffice on the Internet (on the cloud), while the final result is to be published in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available on the following link for download: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0/download300.html. Thus, it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Except for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, you can have the installation CD sent to your home or office.
However, if the freedom of choice is an incentive for the distribution of the programme in the private households, it is precisely in the business area where OpenOffice could succeed in the big throw: after all, various institutions of public administration and schools have already moved to OpenOffice.
In fact, it is not even lacking a training offer, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opening business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word Text Generation Program; Calc, the spreadsheet program, which aims to push Excel; Impress, to create presentations like PowerPoint; Dbase to operate databases instead of the more known access; and lastly Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a goal that can easily be exceeded at already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
