Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historical cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinema halls is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This image of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the large urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-sail complexes in the periphery, means in the long term death for the single cinema in the centre. A process that not only seems inexorable and irrevocable, but also carries the trains of a cultural crime.
Affected are mostly historical places full of memories, "it is like losing a friend with whom a piece of street has been covered with emotion," said the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oskar and the great prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It is the story of an urban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a probably forever lost cinema world.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: over the past five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these pieces paid for most of the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This testifies to the fact that the main culprits are the multiplexkinos, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas have been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years the Lombardy has introduced the lists, 81 are both in Tuscany and Emilia Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, President of Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but first of all, the preservation of the already existing, because closing a hall in the city, are not all his regular customers willing to visit instead of the old one multiplexkino in the periphery.
And here is the lack of a budget for the external trade union fund: the debt burden recorded by the state is about EUR 10 million.
It is a disgrace from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not observe the existing laws.
In order to obtain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be necessary".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, because of the fears about the old cinema halls, has decided to protect it by means of an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first such agreement in Italy, which aims to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
The measures envisaged include tax advantages for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be possible to travel to the traffic restricted areas of the centre and also to park at less favourable parking fees.
"It is a gratifying initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
But certainly we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to set up something against the superpower of multiplex rooms, because finally the audience of today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closing of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "NUovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the thought for ten years.
For 25 years I have been living in Rome; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to see the dusty posters.
