When the energy comes out of the waves, suddenly the greats come up.
It is an unsealed source of money that covers over 70% of the surface of the planet and only now seems to understand the great energy companies of the world.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now looking at all, and are also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; these studies have not by chance intensified significantly since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke down around 1980, the idea of marine energy was forgotten, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pressing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the worldwide energy demand could be met by ocean waves.
This would equal the double of the current energy produced by nuclear power stations.
In addition, the currents and tides would be added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company that now relies on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are relying on marine energy production.
"Chevron investigates these technologies" – the speaker of a U.S. giant-known company in the Wall Street Journal – and weighs the opportunity to work with us."
It is about obtaining approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the Alaska coast.
This is an inestimable sign, especially considering that oil is still being promoted by the US in Alaska and President Bush recently initiated the plans for new drilling.
Besides Chevron, the Verdant Power Inc. companies from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; the details are also unknown, so do observers speak of an increasing interest.
Irreformable technologies.
Experts speak of a technology that is still emerging, not least because the last doubts have not been clarified by the environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of rather small dimensions and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are various possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which move the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the swimmers via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent via underwater pipelines to the coast.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy gained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power, however, already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot with the help of underground turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides stimulate the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Generation Research, a special interest is immediately worthy of the potential that exists in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely the tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska and other coastal states to invest already 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million are planned for 2009.
